<subSubSection id="B7AF650127066D5EFF0950D2F5EFFE64" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="FF0A368A27066D5EFF0950D2F5EFFE64" blockId="4.[151,1436,151,608]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis id="CDC1EA9827066D5EFF0950D2F43EFF53" bold="true" box="[151,273,151,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Dorsal-fin rays VIII + I, 
<number id="497D24AD27066D5EFDBA50D2F75FFF4C" box="[548,624,151,175]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="25.5" valueMax="27.0" valueMin="24.0">24–27</number>
; anal-fin rays II + I, 
<number id="497D24AD27066D5EFCD050D2F6B5FF4C" box="[846,922,151,175]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="21.5" valueMax="23.0" valueMin="20.0">20–23</number>
; scales in curved part of lateral line 
<number id="497D24AD27066D5EFAB050D2F05BFF4C" box="[1326,1396,151,175]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="46.0" valueMax="50.0" valueMin="42.0">42–50</number>
(of which 
<number id="497D24AD27066D5EFF7D50F9F423FF37" box="[227,268,188,212]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="1.0" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="0.0">0–2</number>
posteriorly are scutes); straight part of lateral line with 
<number id="497D24AD27066D5EFCE150F9F686FF37" box="[895,937,188,212]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="3.5" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="0.0">0–7</number>
scales and 
<number id="497D24AD27066D5EFBB550F9F15FFF37" box="[1067,1136,188,212]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="58.5" valueMax="69.0" valueMin="48.0">48–69</number>
scutes; gill rakers (including rudiments) 
<number id="497D24AD27066D5EFED9509AF450FF14" box="[327,383,223,247]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="10.5" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="9.0">9–12</number>
+ 
<number id="497D24AD27066D5EFE3C509AF4C4FF14" box="[418,491,223,247]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="24.5" valueMax="26.0" valueMin="23.0">23–26</number>
; body moderately elongate, the depth about 3.0– 
<quantity id="384D9B6F27066D5EFB81509AF14FFF14" box="[1055,1120,223,247]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.89" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" unit="in" value="3.5">3.5 in</quantity>
fork length; maxilla nearly straight posteriorly; supramaxilla relatively large with an anterior, spine-like projection; last ray of second dorsal and anal fins subequal to penultimate ray; bluish silver dorsally, silvery on side and ventrally, with a diffuse blackish blotch posteriorly on opercle at level of eye; posterior margin of caudal fin blackish. Largest specimen, 
<quantity id="384D9B6F27066D5EFAC85109F0B3FE87" box="[1366,1436,332,356]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.6" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" unit="cm" value="56.0">56 cm</quantity>
TL.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B7AF650127066D5EFF5B51D6F1F4FE2C" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="FF0A368A27066D5EFF5B51D6F1F4FE2C" blockId="4.[151,1436,151,608]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis id="CDC1EA9827066D5EFF5B51D6F471FE4F" bold="true" box="[197,350,403,428]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Distribution.</emphasis>
Ranges from the southern Red Sea and Arabian Gulf in continental waters of south Asia to northwestern and northern 
<collectingCountry id="87A2761A27066D5EFE5B51F2F700FE2C" box="[453,559,439,463]" name="Australia" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Australia</collectingCountry>
, throughout the Indo-Malayan region, and north to Okinawa.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B7AF650127066D5EFF5B5199F17EFDBC" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="FF0A368A27066D5EFF5B5199F17EFDBC" blockId="4.[151,1436,151,608]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis id="CDC1EA9827066D5EFF5B5199F416FE17" bold="true" box="[197,313,476,500]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Remarks.</emphasis>
The Red Sea record is based on the underwater photograph of 
<figureCitation id="678E2A0F27066D5EFC6A5199F17EFE17" box="[1012,1105,476,500]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,2009,2032]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1173,1985]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,1133,1986]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Alepes vari, underwater photograph, Hanish Islands, Yemen (J. E. Randall)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/202772/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">
Figure 
<number id="497D24AD27066D5EFBDD5199F17EFE17" box="[1091,1105,476,500]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
taken by the second author at the Hanish Islands, 
<collectingCountry id="87A2761A27066D5EFEE65245F4E9FDF4" box="[376,454,512,535]" name="Yemen" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Yemen</collectingCountry>
(
<number id="497D24AD27066D5EFE4651BAF4DAFDF4" box="[472,501,511,535]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="13.0">13</number>
° 
<number id="497D24AD27066D5EFD9951BAF70CFDF4" box="[519,547,511,535]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="45.0">45</number>
ʹ N, 
<number id="497D24AD27066D5EFDCA51BAF75DFDF4" box="[596,626,511,535]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="42.0">42</number>
° 
<number id="497D24AD27066D5EFD1C51BAF7B1FDF4" box="[642,670,511,535]" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" value="45.0">45</number>
ʹ E). The identification as 
<taxonomicName id="38B54D0927066D5EFC595245F168FDFB" box="[967,1095,512,536]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Carangidae" genus="Alepes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="4" pageNumber="53" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vari">
<emphasis id="CDC1EA9827066D5EFC595245F168FDFB" box="[967,1095,512,536]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="53">Alepes vari</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was confirmed by William F. Smith-Vaniz. This carangid fish is usually seen in shallow coastal waters, including mangrove areas, often in small groups. It feeds mainly on the larger crustaceans of the zooplankton and small fishes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
